# Auth Service - Cursor Rules

## Project Overview
Java 21 Spring Boot 3.2 authentication and authorization service.
OAuth2/OIDC provider with JWT, 2FA (TOTP), RBAC, session management.

## Tech Stack
- Java 21, Spring Boot 3.2.2
- Spring Security + Spring Authorization Server
- PostgreSQL (JPA/Hibernate), Redis (session/token cache)
- Flyway for database migrations
- jjwt for JWT token handling
- Bucket4j for rate limiting
- Gradle build system

## Project Structure
- `src/main/java/com/facebook/auth/`
  - `config/` - Security, JWT, Redis, OAuth2, rate limit config
  - `controller/` - REST controllers (Auth, User, Session, TwoFactor)
  - `service/` - Business logic
  - `model/entity/` - JPA entities
  - `model/dto/` - Request/Response DTOs (Java records)
  - `repository/` - Spring Data JPA repositories
  - `security/` - JWT provider, auth filter, user details service
  - `exception/` - Error codes, exception handler
- `src/main/resources/db/migration/` - Flyway SQL migrations
- `src/test/` - Unit tests (Mockito) + Integration tests (TestContainers)

## Commands
- Build: `./gradlew build`
- Test: `./gradlew test`
- Run: `./gradlew bootRun`
- Lint: `./gradlew checkstyleMain checkstyleTest`

## Security-Critical Rules
- NEVER log or expose JWT secrets, passwords, or tokens
- NEVER weaken SecurityConfig without explicit security team approval
- Password hashing: BCrypt only (strength 12)
- JWT: HS256 minimum, prefer RS256 for production
- All auth endpoints must be rate-limited
- Always validate @Valid on request DTOs

## Database Migration Rules
- New migrations: `V{next_number}__{description}.sql`
- NEVER modify existing migration files
- NEVER drop columns in production migrations (add new, deprecate old)
- Always provide rollback strategy in migration comments

## Do NOT
- Do not disable CSRF protection
- Do not store plaintext passwords or tokens
- Do not expose internal error details in API responses
- Do not modify RBAC permission seeds without admin approval
- Do not add new OAuth2 grant types without security review
